Date:ABSTRACT
Decentralized Zero Trust Network Access with AI Security
Contemporary educational IoT network architectures predominantly rely on centralized
authentication and access control frameworks that expose critical single points of failure
and introduce significant latency overhead. This research presents a Decentralized Zero
Trust Network Access (DZTNA) system that addresses these fundamental vulnerabilities
through the integration of customized Hyperledger Fabric blockchain for immutable device
identity management, Software-Defined Networking (SDN) enforcement via the Ryu
controller, and TensorFlow Lite-powered AI anomaly detection for real-time threat
identification and mitigation.
The proposed system implements a Zero Trust security model in which every network
device is continuously verified before being granted access, with no entity receiving
implicit trust regardless of its network position. A Python/Flask blockchain ledger
employing SHA-256 cryptographic block linking maintains a tamper-proof single source
of truth for device authorization status. The Ryu-Blockchain middleware intercepts
OpenFlow Packet-In events, extracts MAC addresses, and performs real-time REST API
validation against the distributed ledger, enforcing immediate packet denial for
unauthorized devices. AI-based anomaly detection running on edge hardware monitors
network flow patterns and generates alerts for DDoS attempts, unauthorized access
patterns, and behavioral deviations.
Experimental evaluation demonstrates that the system eliminates the 50% latency increase
associated with cloud-dependent authentication while maintaining offline resilience
through local blockchain replication. The architecture achieves sub-100ms authentication
decisions for registered devices and provides tamper-proof audit trails for all access events.
Comparison against traditional centralized authentication systems shows a 78% reduction
in authentication-related single-point-of-failure incidents and near-zero false negative rates
for unauthorized device detection in controlled test environments. These findings
demonstrate that decentralized Zero Trust principles are technically feasible in resource-
constrained educational settings, offering a robust, privacy-preserving security framework
for IoT-enabled smart classrooms.
Keywords: Zero Trust Architecture, Hyperledger Fabric, Software-Defined Networking,
AI anomaly detection, IoT security, blockchain authenticationACKNOWLEDGEMENTS
