The gap analysis reveals four primary deficiencies in existing systems. First, no existing
solution designed for resource-constrained educational IoT deployments combines all three
security layers: blockchain-based decentralized identity, SDN-enforced access control, and
AI-driven behavioral anomaly detection. Commercial solutions such as Azure IoT Hub
Defender provide AI-based anomaly detection and partial Zero Trust enforcement but
require cloud connectivity and impose per-device subscription costs that are prohibitive for
developing-region educational institutions operating on constrained budgets.
Second, existing blockchain-based IoT authentication frameworks have been designed for
industrial or enterprise contexts with adequate computational resources, reliable network
connectivity, and dedicated IT staff. The specific constraints of educational IoT —
heterogeneous student-owned and institution-owned devices, intermittent internet
connectivity, absence of dedicated network security personnel, and sensitivity of student
behavioral data — have not been adequately addressed.
Third, the integration of Zero Trust principles with SDN policy enforcement at the
OpenFlow level, using blockchain-validated device identity as the trust anchor, represents
a novel architectural combination not present in existing literature. Prior work has
examined blockchain-SDN integration for enterprise traffic engineering but not for Zero
Trust access control in IoT environments.
Fourth, AI anomaly detection for IoT classroom networks has not been evaluated in the
context of the specific traffic patterns generated by multi-modal student monitoring
systems, which combine behavioral analysis data streams, environmental sensor telemetry,
attendance records, and network management traffic in a single shared network.
1.3 Research Problem
Centralized authentication architectures for IoT-enabled smart classroom networks are
fundamentally vulnerable to single-point-of-failure attacks, introduce unacceptableauthentication latency for real-time IoT operations, and fail to detect post-authentication
security breaches resulting from device compromise. Approximately 80% of deployed
educational IoT systems depend on cloud-hosted authentication services, creating latency
increases of up to 50% relative to local processing and introducing privacy risks for
sensitive student behavioral data transmitted to external cloud providers.
Traditional perimeter-based security models are inadequate for the dynamic, heterogeneous
device environments characteristic of smart classrooms, where the attack surface spans
student-owned devices, institutional IoT sensors, edge computing gateways, and network
infrastructure components, each potentially controlled by different stakeholders with
varying security postures. The absence of continuous device verification mechanisms
means that a single compromised device within the trusted perimeter can execute lateral
movement attacks, data exfiltration, or DDoS participation without triggering security
alerts.
Existing solutions do not simultaneously address the three critical requirements for secure,
resilient, cost-effective smart classroom IoT networks in resource-constrained educational
environments: (1) tamper-proof, decentralized device identity management that maintains
operational continuity during network partitions; (2) zero-trust access control enforced at
the network infrastructure layer; and (3) AI-driven behavioral anomaly detection capable
of identifying compromised devices that have successfully authenticated.
1.4 Research Objectives
