2.1 System Design and Architecture
2.1.1 Overview of the Three-Layer DZTNA Architecture
The Decentralized Zero Trust Network Access system is architected across three
functionally distinct but tightly integrated layers. The Identity Layer provides blockchain-
based device identity management using a customized Python/Flask distributed ledger
implementing SHA-256 cryptographic block linking. The Enforcement Layer provides
real-time access control via the Ryu SDN controller, which enforces blockchain-validated
authorization decisions on all network traffic through OpenFlow flow modification
commands. The Intelligence Layer provides AI-driven behavioral anomaly detection using
TensorFlow Lite models deployed on edge hardware, continuously monitoring network
flow statistics for indicators of compromise or attack behavior. The interaction between
these layers creates a defense-in-depth security posture in which each layer provides
independent security guarantees while simultaneously reinforcing the effectiveness of the
other layers.
The system architecture is designed for deployment on a personal laptop or low-cost edge
device (Raspberry Pi 4 with 8 GB RAM or equivalent) that serves as the combined security
gateway and edge computing node. This deployment model eliminates the need for
dedicated server hardware, reducing total deployment cost to approximately LKR 50,000
in material costs while maintaining enterprise-grade security capabilities. Offline logs
synchronize with a central repository when internet connectivity is available, enabling
multi-classroom deployments to share threat intelligence without continuous cloud
dependency.
2.1.2 Blockchain Identity Layer Design
The blockchain identity layer implements a simplified but cryptographically rigorous
distributed ledger optimized for the specific requirements of IoT device authentication.
Rather than deploying full Hyperledger Fabric — which requires Java Virtual Machine
infrastructure and multiple peer nodes — the implementation uses a custom Python/Flask
blockchain that captures the essential security properties of distributed ledger technology
at a fraction of the deployment complexity.
Each block in the ledger encodes the following fields: block index (sequential integer),
timestamp (Unix epoch with millisecond precision), device MAC address, authorization
status (authorized or revoked), previous block hash (SHA-256 of the preceding block's
complete content), and current block hash (SHA-256 of all fields including the previous
hash). The SHA-256 chaining property ensures that any retroactive modification of a
historical authorization record — for example, attempting to backdate a revocation or
falsely insert an authorization — would invalidate all subsequent block hashes, making the
tampering immediately detectable through chain verification.
The ledger exposes three primary REST API endpoints: POST /register for adding new
devices to the authorized registry, POST /revoke for revoking device authorization and
appending a revocation block, and GET /check for real-time authorization status queries
that return a JSON response including authorization status, last action timestamp, and chain
integrity verification result. The /check endpoint is designed for sub-10ms response time to
meet the latency requirements of real-time Packet-In processing in the Ryu middleware.2.1.3 Ryu-Blockchain Middleware and Zero Trust Enforcement
The Ryu-Blockchain middleware is implemented as a custom Ryu application that
intercepts the OpenFlow Packet-In event generated by the Open vSwitch (OVS) data plane
whenever an unknown packet arrives at a network switch. The middleware extracts the
eth.src field (MAC address of the originating device) from the OpenFlow Packet-In
message and performs a synchronous REST API GET request to the blockchain /check
endpoint.
The Zero Trust enforcement logic implements strict Implicit Deny as its default policy. If
the blockchain API returns authorized: False — either because the device MAC address is
absent from the registry, because a revocation block has been appended to its ledger entry,
or because the blockchain chain integrity check fails — the Ryu controller takes no action
on the Packet-In event. The absence of an installed flow rule means that the OVS switch
will continue generating Packet-In events for subsequent packets from the same source,
none of which will receive a forwarding rule, effectively silently dropping all traffic from
the unauthorized device without generating network error messages that could aid an
attacker in fingerprinting the security enforcement mechanism.
If the blockchain API returns authorized: True, the Ryu controller installs a bidirectional
flow rule with idle_timeout=30 seconds, enforcing continuous re-verification of device
authorization at 30-second intervals. This re-verification interval is aligned with the Zero
Trust principle of per-session access control, ensuring that a device whose authorization is
revoked between re-verification cycles is denied access within 30 seconds rather than
remaining authorized until its session terminates. A Table-Miss flow rule installed at startup
ensures that all traffic from unknown devices is redirected to the controller for scrutiny,
with no traffic receiving default forwarding without explicit authorization.
2.1.4 Network Architecture and Communication Flow
The network topology is implemented using Mininet, the software-defined network
emulator, which creates a virtualized network environment comprising one OpenFlow 1.3
switch (Open vSwitch), the Ryu SDN controller connected via the control channel, the
blockchain Flask server accessible at a fixed IP endpoint, and the TensorFlow Lite anomaly
detection process monitoring the switch's mirrored traffic port. This architecture can be
directly translated to physical hardware by replacing the Mininet virtual switch with a
physical OpenFlow 1.3-capable switch and running the Ryu controller on the edge gateway
device.
Traffic flow authentication proceeds as follows. A classroom IoT device initiates network
communication by sending its first packet. The OVS switch, lacking an installed flow rule
for this device, generates a Packet-In event to the Ryu controller. The Ryu middleware
extracts the device MAC address and queries the blockchain. The blockchain performs
chain integrity verification and returns the authorization status. If authorized, Ryu installs
a flow rule; if unauthorized, the packet is silently dropped. The entire authentication
decision completes within 80-120ms under typical conditions, acceptable for initial device
connection while transparent to application-layer protocols.
