2.2.1 Ryu SDN Framework
Ryu is a component-based SDN framework implemented in Python that provides
OpenFlow protocol libraries and an event-driven application interface for implementing
custom SDN control plane logic. Ryu's OFPPacketIn event handler provides the integration
point for the Zero Trust enforcement logic, receiving notification of every unknown packet
arriving at the OVS switch and enabling the synchronous blockchain authorization check
before making forwarding decisions. Ryu's thread-safe event loop and REST API
integration capabilities enable the simultaneous operation of the packet processing loop,
the blockchain query client, and the network monitoring interface without deadlocks or
race conditions.
2.2.2 Custom Blockchain Ledger
The blockchain ledger is implemented in pure Python using only the standard library
hashlib module for cryptographic operations, eliminating external dependencies that might
present compatibility issues on resource-constrained edge hardware. The SHA-256 hash
function is applied to the concatenation of all block fields (index, timestamp, MAC address,
status, previous hash) to produce the current block hash. This construction ensures that even
a single-bit modification to any historical record produces a completely different hash
value, invalidating the chain from the modified block onwards. The Flask REST server
provides thread-safe concurrent access to the ledger, supporting simultaneous authorization
queries from multiple Ryu threads during peak classroom activity.2.2.3 TensorFlow Lite Anomaly Detection
TensorFlow Lite provides the inference runtime for the anomaly detection neural network,
which is trained offline using the CIC-IDS-2017 and CIC-IoT-2023 benchmark datasets
and then exported as a .tflite flat buffer for edge deployment. The training pipeline uses
scikit-learn for feature preprocessing (standardization, PCA dimensionality reduction) and
TensorFlow Keras for model architecture definition and training. The deployed model is a
three-layer feedforward neural network with ReLU activation, trained to classify network
flows into seven categories: Normal, DDoS, Port Scan, Brute Force, Web Attack,
Infiltration, and Bot. Post-training quantization reduces the model size from approximately
4 MB to 1.1 MB with less than 2% accuracy degradation, enabling rapid loading and
inference on Raspberry Pi hardware.
2.3 AI Anomaly Detection and Threat Mitigation
2.3.1 Feature Engineering and Flow Representation
The AI anomaly detection system operates on statistical features extracted from network
flow records captured by monitoring the OVS switch's mirrored port. Flow records are
assembled over 5-second sliding windows, capturing bidirectional traffic statistics between
source-destination IP pairs. The feature set comprises 18 numerical features selected for
their discriminative power in distinguishing normal IoT traffic from attack traffic patterns,
while avoiding features derived from packet payloads to preserve privacy.
