2.3.2 Model Architecture and Training
The anomaly detection model is a feedforward neural network with an input layer of 18
neurons (one per feature), two hidden layers with 64 and 32 neurons respectively using
ReLU activation and 20% dropout regularization, and an output layer of 7 neurons using
softmax activation for multi-class classification. The Adam optimizer with a learning rate
of 0.001 is used for training, with cross-entropy loss function. The model is trained for 50
epochs on 80% of the combined CIC-IDS-2017 and CIC-IoT-2023 dataset (approximately
2.8 million flow samples), with 20% held out for validation.Class imbalance — normal traffic constitutes approximately 83% of samples while certain
attack types represent less than 0.5% — is addressed through a combination of SMOTE
oversampling for minority classes and class-weighted loss function during training. This
approach achieves balanced detection performance across all attack categories without
introducing artificial data artifacts that could reduce generalization to real classroom
network traffic.
2.3.3 Inference Pipeline and Alert Generation
The inference pipeline operates as a background process that reads from a shared queue
populated by the flow feature extraction component. For each completed 5-second flow
window, the pipeline loads the feature vector, applies the saved StandardScaler
transformation, runs TensorFlow Lite inference (approximately 15-25ms on Raspberry Pi
4), and classifies the flow. Flows classified as any attack category with confidence
exceeding 0.85 trigger an alert event that is logged to SQLite, surfaced on the educator
dashboard, and passed to the Ryu controller for automatic flow blocking if the attack type
warrants immediate network-level response (DDoS, Port Scan).
The alert dashboard presents real-time network security status including device
authorization counts, flow classification breakdown, active alert count, and a timeline of
security events. Authorized administrators can review blocked device lists and manually
override automatic blocking decisions, providing human oversight of AI enforcement
actions and compliance with educational institutional governance requirements.
2.3.4 Adversarial Robustness Considerations
The anomaly detection model is evaluated against adversarial evasion attempts in which
DDoS traffic is rate-limited to resemble normal IoT sensor traffic. This evaluation reveals
that purely rate-based features are insufficient for detecting low-rate sophisticated attacks,
motivating the inclusion of temporal pattern features (burst behavior, inter-arrival time
distributions) that capture the statistical signatures of attack traffic even when absolute
traffic volumes are suppressed to blend with normal baselines. The combination of
supervised classification with a separate statistical process control monitor provides
redundant detection coverage that is more robust against single-feature evasion than either
approach alone.
2.4 Commercialization Aspects
2.4.1 Market Opportunity Analysis
The global EdTech security market is projected to reach USD 94 billion in 2025, growing
to USD 186 billion by 2035, driven by accelerating IoT adoption in educational institutions
worldwide and increasing regulatory pressure for student data privacy protection. The
primary target market segment for the DZTNA system is budget-conscious schools and
university administrators in developing regions — particularly South and Southeast Asia
— who require enterprise-grade IoT security capabilities but cannot afford per-device
commercial security subscriptions.
A secondary market segment comprises educational technology companies seeking to
embed Zero Trust security as a differentiating feature in their smart classroom product
offerings. The DZTNA system's open-source core with proprietary enhanced modules
creates a dual licensing opportunity: free open-source deployment for individual
institutions, and a commercial SaaS subscription offering enhanced features includingfederated threat intelligence sharing, automated compliance reporting, and multi-campus
management dashboards.
