2.4.3 Intellectual Property and Value Proposition
The core IP of the DZTNA system lies in the novel Ryu-Blockchain middleware
architecture that bridges OpenFlow SDN enforcement with blockchain-validated Zero
Trust access control. While individual components (Ryu, Mininet, TensorFlow Lite) are
open-source, their integration pattern — specifically the real-time synchronous blockchain
query within the OpenFlow Packet-In processing loop — constitutes a novel technical
contribution that could be protected as a trade secret or filed as a provisional patent in
applicable jurisdictions.
The value proposition for school administrators is compelling: the system provides security
capabilities equivalent to commercial enterprise Zero Trust products at a fraction of the
cost (LKR 10,000/year versus LKR 500,000+/year for comparable commercial offerings),
while operating entirely within the school's premises without student data leaving the
institution's control.
2.5 Testing and Implementation
2.5.1 Unit Testing Strategy
Unit testing covers each of the three major system components independently. The
blockchain ledger unit tests verify SHA-256 hash correctness, chain integrity detection for
modified blocks, authorization status accuracy for registered and revoked devices, and
REST API response format compliance. The Ryu middleware unit tests verify MACaddress extraction from OpenFlow Packet-In events, blockchain query result parsing, flow
rule installation for authorized devices, and silent drop behavior for unauthorized devices.
The TensorFlow Lite anomaly detection unit tests verify feature extraction correctness
against known flow samples, inference output format compliance, and alert threshold
triggering behavior.
