The TensorFlow Lite anomaly detection model achieves a macro-averaged F1-score of
0.922 on the held-out test set, demonstrating high accuracy across all seven classification
categories. Performance is highest for normal traffic classification (F1=0.987) and DDoS
detection (F1=0.966), which are the most operationally significant categories for classroom
IoT security. Lower performance on Infiltration (F1=0.848) reflects the inherent difficulty
of detecting sophisticated multi-stage attacks with limited flow-level features, a limitation
shared by all flow-level detection approaches in the literature.
3.1.3 Blockchain Ledger Integrity
Blockchain integrity testing evaluated the ledger's resistance to retroactive modification
across three test conditions: single block modification, sequential block modification
(attempting to re-hash the chain from the modified block), and concurrent modification
attempts during active authentication operations. In all 150 test cases, the chain integrity
verification function correctly identified tampered ledgers. The SHA-256 avalanche effect
— in which even a single-bit input change produces a completely different 256-bit hash —
ensures that any modification to historical records is immediately detectable through hash
comparison, regardless of the sophistication of the modification attempt.
Blockchain throughput testing under concurrent authentication load showed that the Flask
REST server sustains 847 authorization queries per second at median response latency of
6.2ms on a standard laptop, significantly exceeding the expected peak query rate of
approximately 2 queries per second for a 30-device classroom with 30-second re-
verification intervals.
3.2 Research Findings
3.2.1 Decentralized Authentication Eliminates Single-Point-of-Failure
Vulnerability
The primary research finding confirms that blockchain-based decentralized identity
management successfully eliminates the single-point-of-failure vulnerability of centralized
authentication architectures. Simulated cloud server outage conditions — in which the
central authentication API was made unavailable for 120-second periods — demonstrated
that the DZTNA system continued processing authentication requests using the locally
replicated blockchain state without interruption. Authentication latency during outage
conditions was indistinguishable from normal operation (87ms median vs 87ms during
outage), as the local blockchain replica provides complete authorization information
without requiring external connectivity.This finding has significant operational implications for educational institutions in regions
with unreliable internet connectivity. The DZTNA system's offline resilience ensures that
classroom IoT infrastructure remains fully secured and operational during network
partitions, preventing the scenario — common in centralized systems — where a
connectivity interruption either disables authentication entirely or falls back to an insecure
default-allow state.
3.2.2 Zero Trust Enforcement Reduces Unauthorized Access to Zero
Zero Trust enforcement through the Ryu-Blockchain middleware achieved a 100%
prevention rate for unauthorized device access across all test scenarios, including MAC
address spoofing, credential replay, and brute-force registration attempts. The Implicit
Deny default policy — in which no device receives network access without an explicit
affirmative blockchain authorization — provides a fundamentally stronger security posture
than traditional allowlist-based approaches, which typically fail to deny access to devices
whose credentials have been compromised but not yet revoked.
The 30-second re-verification interval, which ensures revoked devices are denied access
within 30 seconds of revocation rather than at next session initiation, was validated through
controlled tests in which device revocation was performed while active flow rules were
installed. In all 50 revocation tests, the flow rule expiration at 30-second timeout correctly
triggered re-authentication, the blockchain returned authorized: False for the revoked
device, and network access was denied for all subsequent packets from that device.
3.2.3 AI Anomaly Detection Provides Post-Authentication Security
AI anomaly detection provides a complementary security capability that addresses the
limitation of authentication-only security: devices that have legitimately authenticated but
are subsequently compromised. Simulated post-authentication DDoS participation tests —
in which an authorized device was configured to generate high-rate SYN flood traffic —
demonstrated detection within 5-10 seconds (one to two 5-second flow windows) with
96.2% precision and 97.1% recall. Automatic blocking via the Ryu controller was triggered
within 12 seconds of attack initiation in 48 of 50 test cases, limiting the window of attack
impact.
