Table 3.4: System Comparison Against Related WorkThe DZTNA system compares favorably with existing solutions across all evaluation
dimensions. Authentication latency (87ms median single device) is competitive with cloud-
based centralized systems despite the additional blockchain query overhead, demonstrating
that decentralized authentication need not impose significant latency penalties when
implemented with optimized local ledger replication. The combination of full Zero Trust
enforcement, offline resilience, and AI-powered anomaly detection in a single system
deployable at LKR 50,000 represents a significant advance over existing solutions that
provide at most two of these four capabilities simultaneously.
3.3.2 Limitations and Contextual Constraints
The primary limitation of the current implementation is the simplified blockchain ledger
design, which provides strong security guarantees for a single-node deployment but does
not achieve true decentralization across multiple independently operated nodes. Full
Hyperledger Fabric deployment with multiple peer organizations would provide stronger
Byzantine fault tolerance but would require significantly more computational resources
than available on single-node edge hardware. The current architecture is best characterized
as a tamper-evident local ledger with decentralized design principles rather than a fully
decentralized consensus network.
A second limitation is the AI anomaly detection model's training data: the CIC-IDS-2017
and CIC-IoT-2023 datasets, while comprehensive, do not capture the specific traffic
patterns of multi-modal smart classroom IoT deployments. Transfer learning or fine-tuning
on classroom-specific traffic captures would be expected to improve detection accuracy for
classroom-specific attack patterns while maintaining generalization to standard attack
categories.
3.3.3 Ethical and Privacy Considerations
The Zero Trust security model, by its nature, generates detailed logs of every device
authentication event, including device identifiers, timestamps, and network behavior data.
In the context of student-owned devices, this audit trail could constitute personally
identifiable information if device MAC addresses can be linked to individual students. The
system addresses this concern through pseudonymization of device identifiers in audit logs
and role-based access control that restricts full audit log access to network administrators.
Students' learning activities are not monitored or recorded by the security system; only
network-layer metadata required for security enforcement is retained.
