Individual Contribution SummaryCHAPTER 4: CONCLUSION
4.1 Summary of Achievements
This research has successfully designed, implemented, and evaluated a Decentralized Zero
Trust Network Access system that addresses the critical security vulnerabilities inherent in
centralized IoT authentication architectures for educational smart classroom deployments.
The system achieves its primary objective of eliminating cloud authentication dependencies
while maintaining competitive authentication performance and providing enhanced
security through AI-powered behavioral anomaly detection.
The key achievements of this research are:
•
•
•
•
•
A functional Python/Flask blockchain ledger with SHA-256 cryptographic block
linking that provides tamper-proof device identity management, sustains 847
authorization queries per second, achieves sub-10ms query response time in 94%
of requests, and successfully detects 100% of simulated chain tampering attempts.
A Ryu-Blockchain middleware component that enforces Zero Trust Implicit Deny
policy at the OpenFlow level with zero false authorizations across 500
authentication tests and achieves 87ms median end-to-end authentication latency
for single devices.
A TensorFlow Lite anomaly detection system achieving macro-averaged F1-score
of 0.922 across seven attack categories, with sub-25ms inference latency on edge
hardware and automatic DDoS blocking within 12 seconds of attack initiation in
96% of test cases.
A validated offline-resilient architecture that maintains full security operation
during simulated cloud outages of up to 120 seconds, with authentication latency
indistinguishable from online operation.
A commercialization analysis demonstrating achievable return on investment
within two years at modest market adoption rates, with a value proposition
specifically tailored to budget-constrained educational institutions in developing
regions.
4.2 Limitations
Several limitations of the current implementation merit acknowledgement and
contextualisation for future researchers building upon this work.
The simplified blockchain implementation — a single-node Python/Flask ledger rather than
a multi-peer Hyperledger Fabric deployment — provides strong tamper-evidence
guarantees but lacks the Byzantine fault tolerance of a true multi-party distributed
consensus system. In a deployment scenario where the edge gateway device itself could be
physically compromised by an attacker, the single-node architecture would not prevent a
determined adversary from replacing the entire ledger with a fabricated one. Multi-peer
deployment across a school's IT infrastructure would address this vulnerability at the cost
of increased complexity and computational requirements.
The AI anomaly detection model's training on public benchmark datasets (CIC-IDS-2017,
CIC-IoT-2023) rather than classroom-specific traffic captures means that the reported F1-
score of 0.922 may not accurately reflect performance on the specific mix of IoT sensor
telemetry, behavioral analysis data streams, and SDN control traffic present in a real smart
classroom deployment. Domain-specific fine-tuning would be required before productiondeployment to ensure that the model's attack-normal boundary aligns with the actual
baseline traffic characteristics of the target environment.
The Mininet-based evaluation environment, while providing a reproducible and
controllable test platform, does not fully capture the physical layer characteristics of a real
classroom network including wireless interference, RF congestion between multiple
overlapping IoT device networks, and the performance variability introduced by physical
switch hardware. Physical testbed validation on actual classroom infrastructure would
strengthen the generalizability of the performance results.
4.3 Future Work
Several directions for future research would extend the contributions of this dissertation.
Full Hyperledger Fabric integration would replace the custom Python ledger with a
production-grade permissioned blockchain capable of multi-peer consensus across the
school's server infrastructure, providing Byzantine fault tolerance and stronger guarantees
against node compromise. The Ryu-Blockchain middleware interface is designed to be
ledger-agnostic; the REST API endpoint could be replaced with a Hyperledger Fabric peer
query without modification to the SDN enforcement layer.
Federated learning for AI model updates would enable multiple schools deploying the
DZTNA system to collaboratively improve the anomaly detection model by sharing model
gradients rather than raw traffic captures, preserving privacy while enabling continuous
adaptation to evolving attack patterns and classroom-specific traffic baselines. This
direction connects naturally with ongoing research on privacy-preserving collaborative
machine learning in educational contexts.
Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC)-based device certificates, integrated with the
blockchain identity layer, would replace MAC address-based authentication with
cryptographically bound device identities that cannot be spoofed even by an attacker with
physical access to a legitimate device's hardware address. ECC-based authentication on
resource-constrained IoT devices has been demonstrated at sub-50ms latency in recent
literature, suggesting feasibility for integration with the existing Ryu middleware
architecture.
Expansion of the AI security coverage to include lateral movement detection — identifying
authorized devices that attempt to access network segments or services outside their
expected behavioral profile — would address a class of insider threat scenarios not covered
by the current flow-level anomaly detection approach.
4.4 Concluding Remarks
The Decentralized Zero Trust Network Access system developed in this research
demonstrates that enterprise-grade IoT security — combining blockchain-based identity
management, SDN-enforced access control, and AI-powered anomaly detection — is
achievable in resource-constrained educational environments at a fraction of the cost of
commercial security solutions. The system eliminates the single-point-of-failure
vulnerability of centralized authentication while maintaining competitive authentication
latency, providing offline resilience, and detecting post-authentication threats that escape
traditional perimeter-based security controls.
The broader implication of this research extends beyond the specific smart classroom
context. The DZTNA architecture demonstrates a general pattern for deploying Zero Trust
security principles in IoT environments where cloud connectivity cannot be assumed,computational resources are limited, and per-device licensing costs must be minimized.
This pattern is directly applicable to healthcare IoT, industrial IoT, and smart city
deployments in resource-constrained contexts worldwide.
As IoT-enabled educational environments continue to expand in scope and sophistication,
the security of the networks connecting these devices — and the student behavioral data
they collect — becomes an increasingly critical concern. This research contributes a
technically rigorous, practically deployable, and economically viable security framework
that addresses these concerns while remaining accessible to the educational institutions that
need it most.REFERENCES
