Figure A.1 illustrates the complete three-layer DZTNA system architecture. The bottom
layer (Identity Layer) depicts the Python/Flask blockchain ledger with its SHA-256 linked
block chain, REST API endpoints (/register, /revoke, /check), and SQLite persistent
storage. The middle layer (Enforcement Layer) depicts the Ryu SDN controller connected
to the Open vSwitch data plane via the OpenFlow 1.3 control channel, with the Ryu-
Blockchain middleware component shown intercepting Packet-In events and performing
REST API queries to the blockchain layer before installing or withholding flow rules. The
top layer (Intelligence Layer) depicts the TensorFlow Lite anomaly detection process
monitoring the OVS mirrored port, the feature extraction pipeline, the trained model, and
the alert feedback channel to the Ryu controller.
Figure A.2 presents the Ryu-Blockchain Packet-In processing flowchart. The flowchart
begins with the OVS switch receiving a packet from a classroom device and generating a
Packet-In event. The Ryu event handler extracts the eth.src MAC address and issues a GET
/check request to the blockchain REST API. The decision diamond evaluates the authorized
boolean in the API response. The True branch leads to flow rule installation (bidirectional,
idle_timeout=30s) and packet forwarding. The False branch leads to controller inaction and
packet drop. The flowchart annotates the security boundary at which Zero Trust
enforcement occurs.
Figure A.3 shows the complete network communication sequence diagram for a device
authentication and revocation lifecycle: device power-on; first packet and Packet-In event;
blockchain query and authorization; flow rule installation; active session with periodic re-
verification; administrator revocation command; blockchain revocation block append; next
re-verification cycle returning authorized: False; flow rule expiration; subsequent packets
dropped.APPENDIX B: CODE SNIPPETS
Listing B.1: Blockchain Block Structure and SHA-256 Hashing (blockchain.py)
The following code listing presents the core blockchain implementation. The Block
dataclass encodes the device authorization record with SHA-256 chaining. The Blockchain
class manages the ledger, provides chain integrity verification, and exposes the Flask REST
API endpoints for device management and authorization queries.
import hashlib, json, time from flask import Flask, request, jsonify class Block: def __init__(self, idx, mac, status,
prev_hash):
self.index = idx
self.timestamp = time.time()
self.mac = mac
self.status = status
self.prev_hash = prev_hash
self.hash = self._compute_hash() def _compute_hash(self):
content =
json.dumps({
'index': self.index,
'timestamp': self.timestamp,
'mac': self.mac,
'status':
self.status,
'prev_hash': self.prev_hash
}, sort_keys=True)
return
hashlib.sha256(content.encode()).hexdigest() class Blockchain: def __init__(self):
self.chain = [self._genesis()]
def _genesis(self):
return Block(0, "GENESIS", "init", "0") def add_block(self, mac, status):
prev =
self.chain[-1]
block = Block(len(self.chain), mac, status, prev.hash)
self.chain.append(block)
return
block def verify_chain(self):
for i in range(1, len(self.chain)):
if self.chain[i].prev_hash != self.chain[i-
1].hash:
return False
return True def is_authorized(self, mac):
for block in reversed(self.chain):
if block.mac == mac:
return block.status == "authorized"
return False
Listing B.2: Ryu-Blockchain Middleware (zero_trust_app.py)
The RyuBlockchainApp class extends the Ryu RyuApp base class and registers a handler
for the OFPPacketIn event. The handler extracts the source MAC address, queries the
blockchain REST API, and either installs a bidirectional flow rule or allows the packet to
be silently dropped by taking no action.
from ryu.base import app_manager from ryu.controller import ofp_event from ryu.controller.handler import set_ev_cls,
MAIN_DISPATCHER from ryu.ofproto import ofproto_v1_3 import requests BLOCKCHAIN_URL =
"http://127.0.0.1:5000/check" class RyuBlockchainApp(app_manager.RyuApp): OFP_VERSIONS =
[ofproto_v1_3.OFP_VERSION]
@set_ev_cls(ofp_event.EventOFPPacketIn, MAIN_DISPATCHER) def
packet_in_handler(self, ev):
msg = ev.msg
pkt_eth = self._extract_eth(msg)
mac_src = pkt_eth.src
resp = requests.get(BLOCKCHAIN_URL,
params={'mac': mac_src}, timeout=0.5)
data =
resp.json()
if data.get('authorized'):
self._install_flow(msg.datapath, mac_src,
idle_timeout=30)
# Implicit deny: no action taken for unauthorized devicesAPPENDIX C: BLOCKCHAIN LEDGER LOGS
