Table D.1: Network Flow Classification Log (DDoS Simulation)APPENDIX E: DEMO SCREENSHOTS DESCRIPTION
Figure E.1 depicts the DZTNA administrator dashboard interface. The dashboard presents
four primary panels: (1) Device Registry — a table of all blockchain-registered devices
with MAC address, registration timestamp, current authorization status (green badge for
authorized, red badge for revoked), and last-seen time; (2) Authentication Activity — a
time-series chart of Packet-In events per minute, classified by outcome (authorized,
unauthorized, re-verification); (3) AI Security Alerts — a real-time feed of anomaly
detection events with severity classification, source device, attack category, confidence
score, and automated response action; and (4) Blockchain Integrity — a status indicator
showing the most recent chain verification result, total block count, and last block
timestamp.
Figure E.2 presents the device registration workflow interface. An administrator can
register a new device by entering its MAC address and device category (student laptop, IoT
sensor, edge gateway, visitor device). The interface provides immediate feedback
confirming the blockchain block append operation and displaying the new block's hash.
The revocation interface allows administrators to revoke device authorization by MAC
address, with immediate effect on the Zero Trust enforcement layer (all active flow rules
for the revoked device expire at their next 30-second re-verification cycle).
Figure E.3 shows the Mininet network topology visualization generated during the
integration testing phase. The topology depicts one OVS switch connected to thirty IoT
device hosts and the Ryu controller, with the blockchain Flask server and TensorFlow Lite
process running on the controller host. Flow table statistics are overlaid on the switch node,
showing the count of installed flow rules, the Table-Miss rule for unknown device
redirection, and per-port traffic statistics. The visualization validates the correct network
topology instantiation and provides a reference for physical deployment network design.
